      "situation_text": "I am a backend software engineer with 7 years of experience, currently employed at a mid-size fintech company. I have received two job offers and must decide by June 15, 2026 — a firm deadline set by both employers. The first offer is a senior engineer role at a large bank: 95k GBP base salary, standard pension, 30 days leave, but requires 5 days per week in office in central London — a 90-minute commute each way. The second offer is at an early-stage startup: 72k GBP base, 0.8 percent equity vested over 4 years, fully remote, but no pension contribution and a 12-month cliff before equity vests. Key stakeholders: my spouse works part-time and handles school pickup — the commute would require us to hire childcare at approximately 1,200 GBP per month. My current team of 3 junior engineers depends on my technical oversight. The mortgage on our home is 1,850 GBP per month with 18 years remaining; we have 4 months of expenses in savings. Known risks of option 1: commute stress, childcare costs reduce net gain, large employer means slower promotion. Known risks of option 2: startup may fail within 2 years (sector mortality rate approximately 60 percent), equity may be worthless, income reduction of 23k GBP immediately impacts mortgage buffer. I have no other offers pending. My current employer has not made a counter-offer."
    },
